            "creation_date": 1407473662,
            "body": "<p>Your implementation is good, only one minor mistake - in the conditions you should replace <code>=<\/code> with <code>==<\/code> - it's not an assignment - it's a comparison. <\/p>\n\n<p>By the way, what would you expect your method to return for <code>Tx(-1)<\/code> ?<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25196286,
            "question_id": 25196203
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6116845315997f21c5e1187ca6ffc83f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 1098796,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1091751,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1091751/user1234",
                "reputation": 9138,
                "display_name": "user1234"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1407474985,
            "creation_date": 1407473981,
            "body": "<p>Let's start with Tx(2).  n > 1, so we have <code>2*(Tx(n-1) + Tx(n-2))<\/code> which is <code>2*(Tx(1) + Tx(0))<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>But we already know Tx(1) and Tx(0)! So just substitute them in and you get <code>2*(5 + 10) -&gt; 30<\/code>.  Great, so now we know T(2).<\/p>\n\n<p>What about T(3)? <code>2*(Tx(2) + Tx(1))<\/code>.  Nice, we already know these too :) Again, just fill them in to get <code>2*(30 + 5) -&gt; 70<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can work forwards to get to Tx(5).<\/p>\n\n<p>Your code is logically correct, you should just be using <code>==<\/code> to test equality, a single <code>=<\/code> is for assignment.<\/p>\n\n<p>When you run your method, it will work backwards and solve smaller and smaller subproblems until it gets to a point where the answer is known, these are your base cases.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>                    Tx(3)\n  2*    Tx(2)         +        Tx(1)\n  2*Tx(1) + Tx(0)               (5)\n     (5)     (10)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>In order for recursion to work, whatever you are doing each time to break the problem down into smaller problems needs to make some progress towards the base case.  If it doesn't, you will just infinitely recurse until your computer runs out of space to store all of the repeated calls to the same function.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public int Tx(int n) {\n    if(n == 0)\n        return 10;\n    else\n        return Tx(n+1); // n will never reach 0!\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Tx(1) becomes <code>Tx(2) -&gt; Tx(3) -&gt; Tx(4) -&gt; Tx(5)<\/code> etc.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25196331,
            "question_id": 25196203,
            "last_edit_date": 1407474985
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a15ff4107dfc692ff6486019f63b1fcb?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 3270089,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2753662,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2753662/himanshu",
                "reputation": 517,
                "display_name": "Himanshu"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1407476329,
            "creation_date": 1407476329,
            "body": "<p>You have implemented it right just change = with ==. <br/>\nIf you want to further reduce the time complexity you can store the result in an array global to the function so that your function doesnot compute results again and again for a same number this will only save you some time for large computations.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can use something like this.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public int tx(int n , int []arr) {\n     if (arr[n] == 0) {\n          if (n == 1) {\n              arr[n] = 10;\n          }\n          else if (n == 2) {\n              arr[n] = 5;\n          }\n          else {\n              arr[n] = 2 * (tx((n - 1), arr) + tx((n - 2), arr));\n          }\n      }\n      return arr[n];\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25196665,
            "question_id": 25196203
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d78fa94a23d9f29b5a97c681812a4eb9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4804394,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3879992,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3879992/sanket-kumar-mali",
                "reputation": 159,
                "display_name": "Sanket Kumar Mali"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1407474963,
            "creation_date": 1407474963,
            "body": "<p>See whenever you ask the computer for the value Tx(5) it will call the recursive function and so the program will execute the else part because value of n=5.\n  Now in the else part <code>2*(Tx(n-1)+Tx(n-2))<\/code> will be executed.<\/p>\n\n<p>In first iteration it will become <code>2*((2*(Tx(3)+Tx(2)))+(2*(Tx(2)+Tx(1))))<\/code> . The iteration will be continued until the value of n become 0 or 1. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25196459,
            "question_id": 25196203
        }
    ],
